tieth century. While they often disagreed about the role of science and technology in human progress, Julian and Aldous Huxley both believed that the future of our species depends on a saner set of relations with each other and with our environment. Their common concern for ecology has given their ideas about the future of Homo sapiens an enduring resonance in the twenty-first century. The amphibian metaphor that both brothers used to describe humanity highlights not only the complexity and mutability of our species but also our ecologically precarious situation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aHuman ecology. 0aHuman evolution. 7aRELIGION / Comparative Religion.2bisacsh  abiology.  abrave new world.  acomparative religion.  aconservation.  aconservationism.  adystopia.  aecology.  aevolutionary biology.  afuture of our species.  afuture.  ahuman consciousness.  ahuman progress.  ahumanity.  ahuxley brothers.  ainternational politics.  amodern synthesis.  apolitical science.  apolitics.  aprecarious situation.  areligion.  areligious studies.  aresponsibility.  atranshumanism.  atwo brothers.  aunesco.  aunited nations educational scientific and cultural organization.  aunited nations.  aworld wildlife fund.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprintz978052028152340uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095956940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520959569423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520959569/original  a978-3-11-062111-2  University of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY